definition.value: Opening of uterine cervix into the vagina.
An roughly circular indentation in a surface.
A supplemental clasper in Holocephali, in front of the pelvic fin.
Any organ component layer that consists of muscle tissue.
Pelvic clasper organs that have been modified into a flattened structure.
Any organ that is the primary organ of vocalization behavior.
A collection of anatomical structures that are alike in terms of their morphology or developmental origin.
A vascular structure located at the tip of the penis in male mammals or a homologous genital structure of the clitoris in female mammals.
Material anatomical entity that forms the outermost boundary of an anatomical structure.
Fluid that lines the vaginal walls that consists of multiple secretions that collect in the vagina from different glands.
A penis-like organ in male caecilians, which is inserted into the cloaca of the female for several hours.
Eversible phalloid portion of the cloaca that is inserted in the female's vent during copulation. Found in male Caecillians.
The system of organs which serve primarily sexual and reproductive purposes; often only includes the external genitalia to differentiate from the reproductive system.
A variety of language characteristic of a geographical region or ethnic, occupational, socioeconomic, or other group.
Linguistic taxa whose members are based on genetic relatedness.

A term used to describe a language as a whole, with each of its component parts functioning according to an overall convention of usage to enable the members of a speech community to interchange information. Most linguists agree on a 'system of systems', i.e. the arrangement of units on hierarchically ordered and inter-related levels.
The class of taxa whose instances are used in the scientific classification of language varieties. That is, instances of linguistic taxon have instances that are human language varieties.
Taxa are the class of scientific categories used to create a taxonomy and determined according to scientific principles in a given domain.

label.value: subdivision of urogenital part of perineum

definition.value: Subdivision of perineum, each instance of which is a subdivision of the urogenital area of the perineum.

A temporal measurement of the time period elapsed since an identifiable point in the life cycle of an organism. If a developmental stage is specified, the identifiable point would be the beginning of that stage. Otherwise the identifiable point must be specified such as planting (e.g. 3 days post planting).
A developmental stage that forms part of the Sexual Maturity Rating (SMR) Scale, better known as the Tanner Scale.
A Tanner stage characterized by a lack of pubic hair (typically age 10 and younger).

A Tanner stage characterized by a small amount of long, downy hair with slight pigmentation either at the base of the penis and scrotum (males) or the labia majora (typically between ages 10 and 11.5).
A Tanner stage characterized by a hair becoming more coarse and curly, which begins to extend laterally (typically, ages 11.5 to 13).
A Tanner stage characterized by adult-like hair quality, extending across pubis but sparing the medial thighs (typically ages 13 to 15).
A Tanner stage characterized by hair extending to the medial surface of the thights (typically age 15+).
Subdivision of trunk, each instance of which is a regional part of front of trunk; together with the meronymic sum of subdivisions of trunk constitute the trunk.
A region of a free upper limb which is distal to the body.
A group of individual anatomical clusters.
A region of a free lower limb which is distal to the body.
Zone of connectivity where there is no bona fide boundary between some parts of two contiguous structures.
Anatomical cavity, which is surrounded by all morphological parts of an organ; is continuous within the organ; contains one or more body substances.
Excretion in liquid state processed by the kidney.

Originally referring to an endogenous compound that is formed in specialized organ or group of cells and carried to another organ or group of cells, in the same organism, upon which it has a specific regulatory function, the term is now commonly used to include non-endogenous, semi-synthetic and fully synthetic analogues of such compounds.
Cardinal organ part, each instance of which is bounded predominantly by some bonafide boundaries.
Organ segment which is regional part of large intestine.
The distal segment of the large intestine, between the sigmoid colon and the anal canal.
The terminal portion of the gastrointestinal tract, extending from the rectosigmoid junction to the anal canal.
Organ with organ cavity, each instance of which is continuous proximally with some rectum and distally terminates with some anus.

Orifice at the opposite end of an animal's digestive tract from the mouth. Its function is to expel feces, unwanted semi-solid matter produced during digestion, which, depending on the type of animal, may be one or more of: matter which the animal cannot digest, such as bones; food material after all the nutrients have been extracted, for example cellulose or lignin; ingested matter which would be toxic if it remained in the digestive tract; and dead or excess gut bacteria and other endosymbionts.
Organ with organ cavity, each instance of which is proximally continuous with some right ureter and left ureter; distally continuous with some urethra.
An organ zone of the uterus.
The fundus of the uterus is the top portion, opposite from the cervix. Fundal height, measured from the top of the pubic bone, is routinely measured in pregnancy to determine growth rates.
The part of the uterus above the isthmus and below the orifices of the uterine tubes.
Lower, narrow portion of the uterus where it joins with the top end of the vagina.
The lower part of the uterus occupying the region between the isthmus of the uterus and the vagina. It is divided into supravaginal and vaginal portions.
The neck portion of the uterus between the lower isthmus and the vagina forming the cervical canal.
Outer serosa layer of the uterus.

The inside of the uterus. It is triangular in shape, the base (broadest part) being formed by the internal surface of the fundus between the orifices of the uterine tubes, the apex by the internal orifice of the uterus through which the cavity of the body communicates with the canal of the cervix. The uterine cavity of the body of the uterus is a mere slit, flattened antero-posteriorly.
An elongated constriction of the lower part of the uterus, located at the junction of the body of the uterus and the cervix, that is composed principally of smooth muscle.
The internal and external surfaces of the uterus.
The anatomical surface which makes up the anterior part of the uterus.
The anatomical surface which makes up the posterior part of the uterus.
A cutaneous pouch of skin containing the testicles and spermatic cords.
The external sac of skin that encloses the testes. It is an extension of the abdomen, and in placentals is located between the penis and anus.
The musculocutaneous pouch that encloses the testicles.
The pouch that contains the testes and their accessory organs. It is composed of skin, the tunica dartos, the spermatic, cremasteric, and infundibuliform fasciae, and the tunica vaginalis testis.
